# Fluff Date: 2026-02-26 19:50:04
overview:<p>The Behemoth designated BHN-6H represents one of the earliest Stone Rhino chassis to reach the Inner Sphere, a machine stripped of its Clan technology and rebuilt with Succession Wars-era components to serve with Wolf's Dragoons during the Third Succession War. Unlike the Clan-specification Stone Rhinos that would later terrify Inner Sphere defenders during the Clan Invasion, this singular machine was downgraded to Inner Sphere standards at Eden Consolidated Weaponry, trading its advanced Clan weapons and powerplant for cruder but locally maintainable substitutes. Despite these compromises, the hundred-ton BattleMech remained a fearsome battlefield presence that caused mass panic whenever it took the field.</p>

capabilities:<p>The conversion to Inner Sphere technology fundamentally altered the Stone Rhino's performance profile. The original Heavy Force 300 engine was replaced with a two-hundred-rated standard fusion engine, drastically reducing the ’Mech's top speed and making it one of the slowest assault designs on any battlefield. The twin Gauss Rifles gave way to a pair of Autocannon/10s with four tons of ammunition, while the Clan Large Pulse Lasers were swapped for standard PPCs. A single standard Small Laser replaced the original Small Pulse Laser. Twenty-two single heat sinks replaced the original double heat sinks, providing barely adequate cooling for the weapons loadout.</p><p>Despite these downgrades, the Behemoth retained the Stone Rhino's massive frame and substantial armor protection, making it an imposing sight that Inner Sphere forces had no frame of reference to identify. The combination of twin PPCs and Autocannon/10s still delivered considerable firepower at medium range, and the ’Mech's sheer size and unfamiliar silhouette amplified its psychological impact far beyond its actual combat capability. The design's greatest weakness remained its glacial speed, which limited its tactical utility to defensive positions and deliberate assaults.</p>

deployment:<p>The sole BHN-6H configuration replaced the Stone Rhino's Clan weaponry with Inner Sphere equivalents: twin PPCs and Autocannon/10s with four tons of ammunition in place of the original Gauss Rifles and Large Pulse Lasers, and a standard Small Laser replacing the Small Pulse Laser. The 200-rated standard engine reduced the ’Mech's speed considerably, while twenty-two single heat sinks replaced the original doubles. Jump capability was retained but limited by the reduced engine output. This configuration was purpose-built for Wolf's Dragoons service in the Third Succession War, with no further production after the machine's loss at the Battle of Misery.</p>

history:<p>The BHN-6H Behemoth was assigned to Gordon Zed of the Zalman Bloodname, a Trueborn warrior who accompanied Wolf's Dragoons to the Inner Sphere in 3005. Unwilling to leave his Stone Rhino behind, the machine was refitted with Inner Sphere technology at Eden Consolidated Weaponry before the Dragoons' departure, as maintaining Clan-specification equipment in the Inner Sphere would have been impossible without arousing suspicion about the Dragoons' true origins.</p><p>Throughout the Third Succession War, the Behemoth served with the Dragoons' Alpha Regiment, where its unfamiliar hundred-ton chassis caused confusion and panic among opposing forces who had no intelligence files on the design. The ’Mech earned a fearsome reputation despite its technological compromises, a testament to both the robustness of the original Stone Rhino frame and the skill of its pilot. The machine and its warrior fell during the brutal Battle of Misery, one of the bloodiest engagements of the Dragoons' early career in the Inner Sphere.</p><p>Though forces of the Draconis Combine may have salvaged the wreck following the battle, they were never able to repair or reproduce the Behemoth. The unique combination of a Clan-designed frame with Inner Sphere componentry made the ’Mech effectively irreplaceable, and no further BHN-6H models were ever produced. The design remains a historical curiosity, a bridge between the Clan technology that would later transform Inner Sphere warfare and the Succession Wars-era equipment that was the standard of the time.</p>

